{
  "doc_id": "51768",
  "text": "Moreover, the degree of electron localization can be probed through the hyperfine coupling constant (aiso) with the next-neighboring [CITATION_1] O in the electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) spectrum. High values of aiso are expected for localized electrons, low values for delocalized ones. Indeed, the computed aiso is 6.7 MHz for an electron localized on the innermost Ti atom of the NP (see Ti6c core Table 4 ), whereas it is 3.9 MHz for an electron delocalized in the NP core (Core deloc in Table 4 ), in good agreement with experimental observations of a significant decrease of aiso going from a fully localized electron on a single Ti ion (as in the Ti 3+ (H2O)6 complex) [CITATION_2] to shallow electron traps in anatase nanoparticles [CITATION_3] . For the most stable hole trap on the surface, the computed EPR parameters (g = [2.004, 2.015, 2.019] G and A = [31, 30, −97] G) are in excellent quantitative agreement with the g-and A-tensor data available in the experimental literature [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Hence, we may conclude that a correct localization of both charge carriers is provided by the computational models and methods.",
